{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 16:34:29.754267", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — fat-tree EBGP lab\\nTimestamp: now\\n\\n1) Executive summary\\n- Overall network state: healthy. BGP-advertised pod-host prefixes are present throughout the control plane and data-plane ping tests show successful reachability with 0% packet loss and low RTTs for tested hosts.\\n- No device or link appears to be failing; no missing BGP prefixes observed. I did not find routing blackholes or persistent packet loss in the test data.\\n- Minor non-impacting observations (tool invocation / format and minor config oddities) are noted below.\\n\\n2) What I checked (tools used)\\n- Global reachability tests (aggregated ping outputs).\\n- FRR running configurations for: super_spine_router_0, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1.\\n- IP routing tables (show ip route) from each FRR router listed above.\\n- Local network config of hosts pc_0_0 and pc_0_1.\\n- Attempted BGP summary via vtysh through the frr_exec wrapper (that particular call returned an invocation error; BGP state inferred from routing tables and configs instead).\\n\\n3) Key findings and evidence\\n\\nA — Control plane (BGP)\\n- leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200) configuration advertises network 10.0.0.0/24 via BGP (address-family ipv4 unicast).\\n- leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201) configuration advertises network 10.0.1.0/24.\\n- Spine and super-spine configs show EBGP neighbors toward each other using the 172.16.0.x /31 link addresses as expected.\\n- Routing tables (from frr_show_ip_route outputs):\\n  - super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000) has learned 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 (and the other pod prefixes) via the expected spine next-hops (e.g., 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.1). Many pod prefixes are present and marked B (BGP).\\n  - spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1 routing tables contain the expected BGP-learned pod prefixes, and they show multiple alternative next-hops where applicable (consistent with multipath/ECMP/advertisements across multiple spine links).\\n  - leaf routers show their own connected /24s as C (connected) and the rest of the pod prefixes via BGP.\\n- Conclusion: BGP route propagation is functioning; advertised host subnets (10.x.y.0/24) are present at the super-spine and across spines/leaves.\\n\\nB — Data plane (hosts / ping)\\n- Host interface configs:\\n  - pc_0_0: 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1, eth0 UP.\\n  - pc_0_1: 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1, eth0 UP.\\n- Ping/reachability summary (from aggregated get_reachability):\\n  - Most ping pairs tested show 0% loss, low RTTs (in the low single-digit ms range), and stable responses.\\n  - Many inter-pod pings (for a large sample of hosts) succeeded; there is no evidence of packet loss in the sampled tests.\\n- Note: A subset of entries for pc_0_0 in the aggregated reachability output was labeled \"unknown\". However:\\n  - pc_0_0\\'s local interface and routing (ifconfig/ip route) show it is up and has a correct default gateway.\\n  - Other tests that involve networks learned from leaf_router_0_0 show the networks are present in routers\\' routing tables, and other hosts can reach those pod prefixes.\\n  - So the \"unknown\" status is likely due to the reachability tool sampling/selection or test truncation rather than an actual host or network outage.\\n\\nC — Configuration / minor issues\\n- FRR configurations include debug commands: \"debug bgp keepalives\", \"debug bgp updates in\", \"debug bgp updates out\" are present on multiple routers. These generate extra logging but do not indicate failure.\\n- Router IDs:\\n  - super_spine_router_0 router-id is 172.16.0.0 (a network base address). This is unusual but not necessarily a functional problem — router-id must be unique but is usually chosen as a host IP; using .0 may be non-standard.\\n- I attempted to run \"vtysh -c \\'show ip bgp summary\\'\" via the frr_exec wrapper, but that call returned: \"% Unknown command: vtysh -c show\". This appears to be an invocation/wrapping limitation of the wrapper tool rather than an in-network fault. BGP summary could not be directly retrieved via that call; however, route tables already confirm BGP sessions are exchanging prefixes.\\n\\n4) Anomalies (severity: none critical)\\n- Reachability tool produced \"unknown\" status for a couple of pc_0_0 -> destinations; no corroborating evidence of loss or outage elsewhere. Severity: low. Likely tool sampling/truncation or temporary test scheduling issue.\\n- vtysh invocation via frr_exec returned an invocation error. Severity: informational (affects ability to get BGP summary output via that tool).\\n- Router-id value of super_spine_router_0 is set to 172.16.0.0 — unusual practice (informational).\\n\\n5) Device / link localization\\n- No router or link appears to be misbehaving:\\n  - All routers show connected /31 interfaces for the inter-router links.\\n  - BGP-learned prefixes for all advertised /24s are visible on the super-spine and spines/leaves.\\n  - Host interfaces on the two inspected hosts are up and have correct default routes.\\n- Therefore there is no localization to a faulty device or link to report.\\n\\n6) Root cause assessment\\n- There is no evidence of a network fault. BGP control plane and data plane appear to be operating normally.\\n- The few irregularities are due to tool/reporting artifacts:\\n  - The \"unknown\" status entries in aggregated reachability output are not supported by router/host evidence of failure and thus likely a sampling/reporting artifact.\\n  - The failed vtysh invocation is a tooling/command-wrapping issue, not a network protocol failure.\\n\\n7) Additional notes and recommendations for follow-up (diagnostic, not remedial)\\n- If you need explicit BGP session states (established, prefixes/peer counters), re-run the BGP summary directly on the routers (vtysh -c \"show ip bgp neighbors\" or via an execution mechanism that accepts that exact command). The wrapper used here did not accept that form.\\n- If desired, re-run targeted ping tests from a given host (pc_0_0) to specific destinations that were labeled \"unknown\" to rule out intermittent reachability artifacts.\\n- Consider standardizing router-ids to non-network-base addresses for clarity/operational hygiene and remove debug bgp statements in production to reduce log noise — informational only.\\n\\n8) Final conclusion\\n- Network is healthy: BGP is propagating all expected pod /24s, hosts are configured and reachable, and sampled pings show 0% loss.\\n- No faulty devices or links were identified. The only anomalies are tooling/invocation artifacts and a minor non-standard router-id choice.\\n\\nIf you want, I can:\\n- Re-run targeted ping tests from specific hosts that showed \"unknown\".\\n- Attempt alternative commands to obtain BGP neighbor summary/state from each router (using a different wrapper invocation).\\n- Capture specific vtysh outputs if you want precise BGP session state details., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='719bc0ed-303f-4487-a9ab-4caa154406c7'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
